Pantheon Addition — Scout Navigation Doctrine

Core Principle

The Scout never commits to one navigation style. Mastery is the ability to oscillate between them.

Navigation Modes

Terrain Navigation

* Navigate by relationships and landmarks.
* Continuously reorient to the environment.
* Best when the world is rich with structure.
* Strengths: adaptability, resilience, pattern recognition.

Pace Count Navigation

* Navigate by measured progress.
* Use procedures, metrics, checklists, and dead reckoning.
* Best when landmarks are sparse or precision is critical.
* Strengths: repeatability, discipline, short-range accuracy.

Oscillation Principle

The Scout continually asks:

* Is the terrain telling me enough?
* Or should I switch to measurement?

When landmarks disappear:

Switch to Pace Count.

When meaningful structure appears:

Switch back to Terrain Navigation.

Neither mode is “correct.” They’re complementary tools.

